04471nam a22005895i 9780520928442DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209284427 a10.1525/97805209284422doi  a(DE-B1597)648436  a(OCoLC)1408681538  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aNB140.H46 2004eb 7aART0150602bisacsh04a733.309381 aHemingway, Seán, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHorse and Jockey from Artemision :bA Bronze Equestrian Monument of the Hellenistic Period /cSeán Hemingway; ed. by Seán Hemingway. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b10 color illustrations, 73 b/w photographs, 9 line illustrations, 1 map, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHellenistic Culture and Society00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- t1. Hellenistic Bronze Statuary: An Introduction -- t2. An Early Underwater Rescue Excavation -- t3. Technical Analysis -- t4. Questions of Style and Identification -- t5. Ancient Greek Horse Racing -- t6. Conclusions -- tAppendix: Chemical Analysis and Metallographic Examination -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1928, and again in 1937, parts of a large-scale bronze horse and nearly complete jockey were recovered from the sea off Cape Artemision in Greece, where they had gone down in a shipwreck. These original Hellenistic sculptures, known together as the "Horse and Jockey Group from Artemision," are among the very few surviving bronze sculptures from antiquity. Seán Hemingway has been allowed by the National Museum in Athens to investigate the horse and jockey statuary group as no one ever has before, and in this book, combining archaeological and art historical methods of investigation, he provides the first in-depth study of this rare and beautiful monument. New technical analyses of the statues by Helen Andreopoulou-Mangou form an appendix to the volume.Hemingway begins with an introduction to Hellenistic bronze statuary and what we know about this extraordinary class of ancient sculpture. He then recounts with riveting detail the discovery and painstaking restoration of the statue group, describing the technique of its creation and carefully reviewing scholarly knowledge and speculation about it. He also provides a valuable compendium of what is known about ancient Greek horse racing, the most prestigious and splendid of all Greek sports. After a full consideration of all the available evidence, he speculates further about the work’s original meaning and function. His study provides a glimpse of the excellence achieved by Hellenistic bronze sculptors, and it will become the definitive resource on this unique sculpture from ancient Greece.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAncient & Classical. 4aArt. 4aHistory. 7aART / History / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aAndreopoulou-Mangou, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHemingway, Seán, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023308940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092844240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520928442423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520928442/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles